    "29": { correct: "d", correctText: "Mahavamsa", exp: "The Mahavamsa, the Sri Lankan Pali chronicle, contains an account of Emperor Ashoka. The Vinaya, Sutta and Abhidhamma Pitakas are the canonical “baskets,” not historical chronicles of Ashoka." },
    "30": { correct: "c", correctText: "1 and 2", exp: "The Mahavamsa credits Ashoka’s conversion to his nephew Nigrodha (1), and the Divyavadana to the monk Samudra, a merchant-turned-monk (2). Statement 3’s attribution to the Dipavamsa is inaccurate. Hence 1 and 2." },
    "31": { correct: "d", correctText: "Dhamma", exp: "Kautilya’s Saptanga (seven limbs of the State) are Swami, Amatya, Janapada, Durga, Kosha, Danda and Mitra. Dhamma is not one of them." },
    "32": { correct: "c", correctText: "Both 1 and 2", exp: "The Rummindei and Nigali Sagar pillar inscriptions attest Ashoka’s Buddhist faith (1), and Minor Rock Edict I records his change of faith (2). Both statements are correct." },
    "33": { correct: "a", correctText: "Kautilya", exp: "Kautilya (in the Arthashastra) first spoke of food-for-work/relief measures to counteract famines. Aryabhata, Chandragomin and Prabhakara were not associated with this idea." },
    "34": { correct: "c", correctText: "3 (i.e., three statements are correct)", exp: "Statements 1, 3 and 4 are correct — the forest people were brought under new dominance, the State conserved forests and prohibited burning, and forest people served as troops/spies. Statement 2 is wrong — forest produce was the State’s monopoly, not the forest people’s. So three statements are correct." },
    "35": { correct: "b", correctText: "1 and 3 only", exp: "The Sarnath Lion Capital includes the shaft/column (1) and inverted lotus petals below the abacus (3). Statement 2 is wrong — the abacus is carved (with animals and chakras), not “devoid of carvings.” Hence 1 and 3 only." },
    "36": { correct: "b", correctText: "1, 3 and 4 only", exp: "Samahartri = Chief Collector of Revenue (1), Akshapatala = Records-cum-Audit (3), Samnidhatri = Treasurer (4) — all correct. Statement 2 is wrong — Dauvarika was the chief of palace guards/door-keeper, not the Chief of Army (that was the Senapati). Hence 1, 3 and 4." },
    "37": { correct: "d", correctText: "Kalsi in Uttarakhand is a site of Major Rock", exp: "Kalsi (Uttarakhand) is indeed a Major Rock Edict site — this is correct. The Kerala “Sanskrit” claim is wrong, Bihar’s minor edicts are at Sasaram (not only Pataliputra), and the Dhauli edict actually omitted the Kalinga-war edict (RE XIII), so options a, b and c are wrong." },
    "38": { correct: "a", correctText: "Brahmaputra valley, Assam", exp: "Ashoka’s empire covered Baluchistan, North Bengal and the Kashmir valley, but the Brahmaputra valley (Assam/Kamarupa) lay outside its limits. Hence Assam’s Brahmaputra valley is the answer." },
    "39": { correct: "d", correctText: "1 and 3 only", exp: "Some Sanchi sculptures show the Shalabhanjika (1), and this tree-spirit motif was not directly inspired by Buddhist ideas (3). Statement 2 is wrong — a woman surrounded by lotuses and elephants describes Gajalakshmi, not the Shalabhanjika. Hence 1 and 3 only." },
    "40": { correct: "d", correctText: "1, 2 and 3", exp: "Kanaganahalli is on the bank of the Bhima river (1), its stupa is dated to the 1st–3rd centuries CE (2), and a sculpted portrait of Ashoka (“Raya Asoko”) was found there (3). All three are correct." },
    "41": { correct: "d", correctText: "A garland of thousand lotus flowers", exp: "In stupa decoration the term “Kinjalkini” refers to a garland of a thousand lotus flowers (verified). It does not denote creepers, scarves/saris or mango-shaped pendants." },
    "42": { correct: "a", correctText: "an unstitched length of cloth draped around the body", exp: "The antariya was the lower garment of the Mauryan period — an unstitched length of cloth draped around the body. It was not a sewn/sleeved tunic or a head covering." },
    "43": { correct: "c", correctText: "3", exp: "Three pairs match: Girnar–Sudarshana Lake (I), Cholistan–terracotta plough model (II), and Mant near Mathura–headless Kanishka statue (III). Pair IV is wrong — Sannati (with Ashokan edicts) is in Karnataka, not Odisha. Hence 3 pairs are correct." },
    "44": { correct: "b", correctText: "1, 2 and 3 only", exp: "Jain ideas were circulated by Parshva in the 7th century BC (1); neither Buddhism nor Jainism sought to abolish caste (2); and Mahavira’s first female disciple was reportedly a captured slave woman (3). Statement 4 is wrong — Buddha admitted nuns but did not grant them fully equal status. Hence 1, 2 and 3." },
    "45": { correct: "c", correctText: "They were located in rural areas.", exp: "Buddhist stupas were generally located near towns and along trade routes, not specifically in rural areas, so this is the incorrect statement. Ashoka popularising the stupa cult, relics, and trade-route locations are all correct." },
    "46": { correct: "a", correctText: "Majjhima Nikaya", exp: "The dialogue on Varna between King Avantiputta and Kachchana (the Madhura Sutta) appears in the Majjhima Nikaya. It is not in the Samyutta/Anguttara Nikaya or Ambattha Sutta." },
    "47": { correct: "b", correctText: "Khema", exp: "Khema was a chief Buddhist nun (a disciple of the Buddha), not a Jain Acharya. Bhadrabahu and Haribhadra were Jain Acharyas, so Khema is the odd one out." },
    "48": { correct: "b", correctText: "It refers to monks, who migrated to the south of Vindhyas in 4th century BCE", exp: "This statement is incorrect — it was the Digambaras (under Bhadrabahu) who migrated south; the Shvetambaras remained in the north. Shvetambaras wearing white, recognising the 12 Angas, and believing women can attain salvation are all correct." },
    "49": { correct: "d", correctText: "They formed an alliance with Jainas against Buddhists", exp: "This is incorrect — the Ajivikas did not form such an alliance. They did have a corporate organisation and canonical texts, practised severe asceticism, and did not discriminate by caste — those statements are correct." },
    "50": { correct: "b", correctText: "Elder nuns in Buddhism", exp: "“Theris” were the senior/elder Buddhist nuns (their verses form the Therigatha). The term does not mean respected women generally, denied nuns, or expelled women." },
    "51": { correct: "a", correctText: "She was converted by the Buddha from a blood-thirsty yakshi to a benevolent maternal figure", exp: "Hariti was a child-devouring yakshi whom the Buddha converted into a protector of children and a maternal figure. She is not the personification of wisdom or a dawn/warrior goddess." },
    "52": { correct: "b", correctText: "Jaina elements in the storyline", exp: "The Silappadikaram, composed by the Jain prince-ascetic Ilango Adigal, is infused with Jaina ideas such as karma and fate (verified answer). Though it ends with Kannagi’s deification, the exam’s keyed answer is the Jaina elements in its storyline." },
    "53": { correct: "a", correctText: "Cauvery", exp: "The Cauvery (Kaveri) is the river praised in the Silappadikaram. The Godavari, Saraswati and Ganges are not celebrated in that Tamil epic." },
    "54": { correct: "c", correctText: "4, 3, 2, 1", exp: "Kurinchi = mountainous (4), Palai = arid (3), Neytal = seashore (2), Mullai = pastoral/forest (1). This gives A-4, B-3, C-2, D-1 = option c." },
    "55": { correct: "b", correctText: "Sathanar", exp: "Manimekalai (the Buddhist Tamil epic) was authored by Sittalai Sathanar. Ilango Adigal wrote the Silappadikaram; Kovalan is a character, not the author." },
    "56": { correct: "d", correctText: "Pali", exp: "The Gandatindu Jataka, like the other Jataka tales, was composed in Pali. It is not in Sanskrit, Telugu or Tamil." },
    "57": { correct: "d", correctText: "Vellalars", exp: "According to the Sangam texts, the Vellalars were the large landowners. Gahapatis (northern term), Uzhavars (cultivators) and Adimais (slaves/labourers) were different groups." },
    "58": { correct: "d", correctText: "113 years old", exp: "The Hathigumpha inscription of Kharavela records that the confederacy of Tamil States (Tramiradesa Sanghatam) which he broke was 113 years old at that time." },
    "59": { correct: "c", correctText: "A-3 B-4 C-1 D-2", exp: "Maruta Makkal = ploughmen (3), Kuravan Makkal = hill people (4), Mullai Makkal = pastoralists (1), Neytal Makkal = fishing people (2). This gives A-3, B-4, C-1, D-2." },
    "60": { correct: "b", correctText: "Korkai", exp: "Korkai was the important Pandya port celebrated for its pearls in Sangam poems and Greek accounts. Muchiri (Muziris) was Chera, Puhar was Chola, and Arikamedu was a trading site." },
    "61": { correct: "a", correctText: "A work of grammar", exp: "The Tolkappiyam is the earliest extant Tamil work on grammar (and poetics). It is not a praise-poem, a drama or a didactic ethical work." },
    "62": { correct: "d", correctText: "1, 2 and 3", exp: "Madurai is described in the Maduraikkanchi as a grand walled city with the Vaigai on one side (1), the Arthashastra notes its fine cotton textiles (2), and other sources describe it as a major craft centre (3). All three are correct." },
    "63": { correct: "d", correctText: "Tripurantaka", exp: "The Tripurantaka form of Shiva (destroyer of the three cities) is prominently depicted in the Brihadeshvara (Rajarajeshvara) Temple built by Rajaraja I. Harihara, Bhairava and Rudra are not its dominant form." },
    "64": { correct: "b", correctText: "Nattar — Male serpent deity", exp: "This pair is wrong — Nattar referred to the members/assembly of the nadu (a territorial unit), not a serpent deity. Nagarakkani, Yupa and Viragal are correctly matched." },
    "65": { correct: "d", correctText: "1, 2 and 3", exp: "In the Nataraja bronze, Shiva’s planted right leg (on apasmara) represents tirobhava/veiling (1), the raised left leg in bhujangatrasita represents grace/removal of illusion (2), and the upper right hand holds the damaru (3). All three are correct descriptions." },
    "66": { correct: "b", correctText: "Shiva as Yoga-Dakshinamurti", exp: "Among the early Chola murals discovered (1931) at the Brihadisvara Temple, Thanjavur, “Shiva as Yoga-Dakshinamurti” is the noted painting (verified). The Buddha, Yakshi Kali and Parshvanatha options do not belong to these Shaiva Chola frescoes." },
    "67": { correct: "b", correctText: "Rajaraja I", exp: "Rajaraja I permitted/encouraged the Sailendra ruler of Sri Vijaya to build the Chudamani Vihara (Buddhist monastery) at Nagapattinam. It was not Parantaka I, Rajendra I or Kulottunga I." },
    "68": { correct: "c", correctText: "Both 1 and 2", exp: "The Chola period is renowned for the finesse of its metal (bronze) sculpture (1), and the iconography and style of these metal images closely matched their stone counterparts (2). Both statements are correct." },
    "69": { correct: "d", correctText: "Kudumiyamalai", exp: "The musical inscription with groups of notes arranged for pupils (7th–8th century CE) is at Kudumiyamalai (Tamil Nadu). Ennayiram and Uttaramerur are known for educational/assembly inscriptions, not this musical one." },
    "70": { correct: "a", correctText: "Kuddapah-kar — Rocky wastelands", exp: "This pair is the odd one out. Nancai (wet fields), Puncai (dry fields) and Tottakal (garden lands) are correctly matched Tamil land terms, while “Kuddapah-kar — rocky wastelands” is not correctly matched." },
    "71": { correct: "c", correctText: "The Pallavas of Tondaimandalam", exp: "The Pallavas of Tondaimandalam issued their early charters in Prakrit and later switched to Sanskrit. This Prakrit-to-Sanskrit shift is characteristic of the Pallavas, not the Cholas, Pandyas or Gangas (as framed here)." },
    "72": { correct: "c", correctText: "Adivaraha Cave", exp: "The royal portraits of Simhavishnu and Mahendravarman are found in the Adivaraha cave temple at Mamallapuram (Mahabalipuram). They are not in the Varaha, Ramanuja or Trimurti caves." },
    "73": { correct: "d", correctText: "Coins and sculpture", exp: "The Kushana rulers’ notion of kingship/lineage (e.g. the devakula statues at Mat and the deities on their coins) is best evidenced through their coins and sculpture, rather than land grants or panegyrics." },
    "74": { correct: "b", correctText: "Varman Dynasty of Assam", exp: "The Bhaskara who sent presents to Harshavardhana was Bhaskaravarman of the Varman dynasty of Kamarupa (Assan/Assam). He did not belong to the Haryanka or Nanda dynasties." },
    "75": { correct: "b", correctText: "The status of women was redefined… right to property.", exp: "This statement is incorrect — in the Gupta period women’s status actually declined; early marriage was not banned and women generally lacked formal education and full property rights. The statements on Sanskrit’s classical excellence, land grants and feudal/serfdom developments are correct." },
    "76": { correct: "b", correctText: "Arunashva", exp: "After Harshavardhana’s death, his minister Arunashva (Arjuna) usurped power in Kanyakubja and attacked the Chinese envoy Wang Hsuan-tse. Shashanka, Adityasena and Lalitaditya were not the usurper here." },
    "77": { correct: "d", correctText: "The largest number of coins issued by the Guptas were of copper", exp: "This is incorrect — the Guptas issued the largest number of gold coins (Dinaras); they are most famous for their gold coinage. The statements on Dinaras, silver coins of later kings, and obverse/reverse imagery are correct." },
    "78": { correct: "c", correctText: "Samudragupta", exp: "The Prayaga Prashasti (Allahabad Pillar inscription), composed by Harisena, eulogises Samudragupta. It is not about Ashoka, Harshavardhana or Bindusara." },
    "79": { correct: "a", correctText: "Uttar Pradesh", exp: "The Gupta-period Dashavatara (Deogarh) Temple is at Deogarh in the Lalitpur district of Uttar Pradesh. It is not in Madhya Pradesh, Chhattisgarh or Rajasthan." },
    "80": { correct: "c", correctText: "Both 1 and 2", exp: "Ajanta cave paintings depict yakshas, gandharvas and apsaras (1), and the artists used the technique of multiple perspectives/viewpoints (2). Both statements are correct." },
    "81": { correct: "a", correctText: "Yama, Indra, Varuna and Kubera", exp: "The Lokapalas (guardians of the directions/universe) include Indra (east), Yama (south), Varuna (west) and Kubera (north). The other combinations wrongly add Skanda, Brahma or Shiva." },
    "82": { correct: "b", correctText: "1, 2 and 3", exp: "Shankara espoused Advaita Vedanta (1), elaborated on Gaudapada’s philosophy (2), and showed that the Upanishads/Brahmasutras form a unified system (3). The founding of the four mathas (statement 4) is the one left out, giving 1, 2 and 3." },
    "83": { correct: "a", correctText: "Alvars", exp: "The Nalayira Divya Prabandham (a collection of ~4000 Tamil verses) was composed by the Alvars (Vaishnava saints) and compiled by Nathamuni. The Nayanars were Shaiva saints." },
    "84": { correct: "c", correctText: "1 and 2 only", exp: "Brahmadeya grants meant the State renounced revenue (1) and varied from a small plot to several villages (2). Statement 3 is wrong — such grants were not “mostly in unsettled areas.” Hence 1 and 2 only." },
    "85": { correct: "d", correctText: "It is associated with the Pashupata sect.", exp: "The Elephanta caves are Shaiva and associated with the Pashupata sect. The naming was by the Portuguese (not British), it has more than one cave, and its great carving is of Shiva (not Vishnu) — so the other options are wrong." },
    "86": { correct: "a", correctText: "Srirangam", exp: "Srirangam (Ranganatha) is a Vaishnavite temple. Chidambaram, Gangaikonda Cholapuram and Thanjavur (Brihadeshvara) are Shaiva temples." },
    "87": { correct: "c", correctText: "Purva-Mimamsa", exp: "Kumarila Bhatta and Prabhakara were the great exponents of the Purva-Mimamsa school. They did not belong to Lokayata, Madhyamika or Uttara-Mimamsa (Vedanta)." },
    "88": { correct: "d", correctText: "1 and 3 only", exp: "Dhurtta (1) and Sushikshita (3) are recognised Charvaka (materialist) sub-schools. Nyaya (2) and Vaisheshika (4) are orthodox (astika) schools, not Charvaka. Hence 1 and 3 only." },
    "89": { correct: "c", correctText: "Alvars — Believed in devotion of Shakti", exp: "This pair is wrong — the Alvars were devotees of Vishnu, not Shakti. Saguna/Nirguna and the Nayanars (devotees of Shiva) are correctly matched." },
    "90": { correct: "c", correctText: "Andal", exp: "Andal was an Alvar (a Vaishnava woman saint), not a Nayanar. Karaikkal Ammaiyar, Mangayarkkarasiyar and Isaignaniyar were the women among the 63 Nayanars." },
    "91": { correct: "c", correctText: "Leaders who were devotees of Shiva", exp: "The Nayanars were Shaiva saints — devotees of Shiva. The devotees of Vishnu were the Alvars." },
    "92": { correct: "a", correctText: "Those who immersed in devotion to Vishnu", exp: "The Alvars were the Tamil Vaishnava saints, immersed in devotion to Vishnu. Shaiva devotees were the Nayanars." },
    "93": { correct: "c", correctText: "Both 1 and 2", exp: "Shankara founded Advaita Vedanta (1) and Madhva elaborated Dvaita (dualist) Vedanta (2). Both statements are correct." },
    "94": { correct: "d", correctText: "2 and 3", exp: "Gypsies are regarded as of Indian origin because their language Romani is Indo-Aryan (2) and they believe they came from India (3). They do not follow Indian religious practices, and no epigraphic evidence places their home in UP, so 1 and 4 are wrong." },
    "95": { correct: "d", correctText: "Nutmeg", exp: "Pepper, spikenard and tortoiseshell were major Indian exports to Rome in the 1st century AD. Nutmeg (from the Moluccas/Indonesia) was not a major Indian export item then." },
    "96": { correct: "c", correctText: "Arikamedu", exp: "Arikamedu (near Puducherry) is the key site for India’s maritime/Roman trade links on the Coromandel coast. Bharukachchha was on the west coast; Karur and Anuradhapura are not Coromandel ports." },
    "97": { correct: "b", correctText: "Both true & II not explanation", exp: "Greek travellers were impressed by India’s soil fertility and its cultivators (I), and ancient India did know the use of manure (II). Both are true, but knowing manure does not by itself explain their admiration, so II is not the correct explanation." },
    "98": { correct: "c", correctText: "3rd century CE", exp: "In the Gandhara school, schist/phyllite stone was used early, and stucco progressively replaced stone as the main medium by about the 3rd century CE. (Sources vary between the 3rd–4th centuries; among the options 3rd century CE is the intended answer.)" },
    "99": { correct: "c", correctText: "Lakshmidhara", exp: "The 12th-century scholar Lakshmidhara (at the Gahadavala court) first compiled the Nibandhas/digests (Krityakalpataru) of epic and Puranic texts. Harsha, Govindachandra and Kalidasa were not the compilers." },
    "100": { correct: "c", correctText: "Both 1 and 2", exp: "Isampur (Gulbarga, Karnataka, on the Kamta Halla stream) was a Paleolithic stone-tool centre (1), and a Paleolithic blade is a flake tool more than twice as long as it is wide (2). Both statements are correct." },
    "101": { correct: "d", correctText: "It is a text showing through illustration what should and should not be done", exp: "The Panchatantra is a collection of didactic animal fables (niti-shastra) illustrating prudent and imprudent conduct. It is not a philosophical refutation, a linguistics text or a natural-science treatise." },
    "102": { correct: "b", correctText: "2 only", exp: "Patanjali’s Mahabhashya is essentially a work on grammar that refers to historical personalities only incidentally (2, correct). It does not mention Kautilya (statement 1 is wrong). Hence 2 only." },
    "103": { correct: "c", correctText: "A-2 B-3 C-4 D-1", exp: "Duta (Dutavakya/Dutaghatotkacha) = Bhasa (2), Mrichchhakatikam = Shudraka (3), Kiratarjuniyam = Bharavi (4), Ravanavadha (Bhattikavya) = Bhatti/Ghatotkacha (1). This gives A-2, B-3, C-4, D-1." },
    "104": { correct: "d", correctText: "Manjushrimulakalpa", exp: "Ashvaghosha wrote the Buddhacharita, Saundarananda and Sariputraprakarana. The Manjushrimulakalpa is a later Mahayana tantric text, not his work." },
    "105": { correct: "c", correctText: "Ashtadhyayi", exp: "Panini’s Ashtadhyayi (c. 5th–4th century BCE) is the earliest of the listed texts. The Natyashastra, Sushruta Samhita and Manusmriti were composed later." },
    "106": { correct: "c", correctText: "He belonged to a period between Panini and Patanjali", exp: "Katyayana, the vartikakara (commentator on Panini’s sutras), lived after Panini and before Patanjali. Hence he belongs to the period between the two grammarians." },
    "107": { correct: "a", correctText: "1, 2 and 3 only", exp: "Puranas (1), the Ramayana (2) and Kalpa-Sutra (3) are smriti literature. The Vedas (4) are shruti, not smriti. Hence 1, 2 and 3 only." },
    "108": { correct: "b", correctText: "Vishnu Purana", exp: "The legend of Prahlada and his father Hiranyakashipu was first set out in the Vishnu Purana (and later elaborated in the Bhagavata Purana). Hence the Vishnu Purana is the answer." },
    "109": { correct: "b", correctText: "Kunta", exp: "Sharnga, Kodanda and Karmuka all denote the bow (a bow-and-arrow weapon). Kunta means a spear/lance, so it does not refer to the bow and arrow." },
    "110": { correct: "c", correctText: "1 and 2 only", exp: "The Bakhshali Manuscript deals with fractions, square roots and progressions (1), and Aryabhata gave pi ≈ 3.1416 (2). Statement 3 is wrong — the Sharangadhara Samhita is a medical text, not a treatise on political systems. Hence 1 and 2 only." },
    "111": { correct: "a", correctText: "Andhra Pradesh", exp: "The Guntupalle (Guntupalli) Buddhist rock-cut caves are located in Andhra Pradesh (Eluru district). They are not in Karnataka, Tamil Nadu or Kerala." },
    "112": { correct: "b", correctText: "Balban", exp: "Ghiyasuddin Balban finally broke and destroyed the power of the Turkan-i-Chihalgani (the “Forty” Turkish nobles) to centralise royal authority. Iltutmish had created the Forty; Alauddin Khalji and Muhammad bin Tughluq came later." },
    "113": { correct: "a", correctText: "Chenghiz Khan", exp: "Genghis (Chenghiz) Khan reached the Indus pursuing Jalaluddin Mangabarni but did not cross it to attack India. Tair Bahadur, Abdullah and Qutlugh Khwaja led Mongol incursions across the Indus into India." },
    "114": { correct: "b", correctText: "Muhammad bin Tughluq", exp: "Ibn Battuta was sent as an envoy to China by Sultan Muhammad bin Tughluq. He served as a qazi at the Sultan’s court before the mission." },
    "115": { correct: "c", correctText: "Panna", exp: "Diamond mining during the Delhi Sultanate period was carried out at Panna (in present-day Madhya Pradesh), a long-famous diamond region. Awadh, Khambhat and Lakhnauti were not diamond-mining centres." },
    "116": { correct: "d", correctText: "Nuh Sipihr", exp: "In Nuh Sipihr (“Nine Skies”), Amir Khusrau praised India’s climate, its languages (especially Sanskrit), its arts, music and animals. The other works deal with different themes." },
    "117": { correct: "b", correctText: "3, 1, 2, 4", exp: "Chronologically: Qutub Minar (begun c. 1199) → Tughlaqabad Fort (1321) → Bada Gumbad, Lodhi Garden (late 15th c.) → Fatehpur Sikri (1571). This is 3, 1, 2, 4." },
    "118": { correct: "b", correctText: "Abul Hasan", exp: "The allegorical Mughal painting of Jahangir embracing Shah Abbas was by Abul Hasan (“Nadir-uz-Zaman”). Abd al-Samad and Dasavant belonged to Akbar’s atelier; Bishandas painted Shah Abbas’s portrait from life but not this allegory." },
    "119": { correct: "c", correctText: "Sirat-i-Firuz Shahi", exp: "The painted illustration of the moving of the Topra Ashoka Pillar (by Firuz Shah Tughluq) appears in the Sirat-i-Firuz Shahi. The Tarikh-i-Firuz Shahi and Akbar Nama do not contain this illustration." },
    "120": { correct: "d", correctText: "Neither 1 nor 2", exp: "Statement 1 is wrong — Ellora is associated with three religions (Buddhist, Hindu, Jain), not exclusively Buddhism. Statement 2 is wrong — the Kailasa temple is monolithic rock-cut, not built of dressed stone and bricks. Hence neither is correct." },
    "121": { correct: "b", correctText: "1, 2 and 3", exp: "Kabir’s verses are preserved in the Bijak (Varanasi), the Kabir Granthavali (Rajasthan) and the Adi Granth Sahib (Sikh tradition). All three traditions are correct." },
    "122": { correct: "d", correctText: "1, 2 and 3", exp: "Sufi silsilas signified a continuous master-disciple link (1), an unbroken spiritual genealogy to the Prophet (2), and the transmission of spiritual power/blessings (3). All three are correct." },
    "123": { correct: "d", correctText: "Hujwiri’s conversation with the Yogis shows that he was impressed with their theory of the division of the human body. (Flagged — specialised question)", exp: "Al-Biruni’s comparisons of Sufi divine love and soul-theory with the Gita and Patanjali, and the impact of the Amrita Kunda on Sufism, are well documented (a, b, c correct). The statement about Hujwiri being impressed by yogic body-division theory is the odd/incorrect one. (This is a specialised question; please cross-check with the official key.)" },
    "124": { correct: "a", correctText: "Ginan", exp: "The Khojas (a branch of the Ismaili sect) developed the devotional literary genre called Ginan. Ziyarat, Raag and Shahada are not this Khoja genre." },
    "125": { correct: "a", correctText: "Shihabuddin Suhrawardi", exp: "The idea of Farr-i Izadi (divine effulgence), underpinning Mughal kingship, traces to the Illuminationist (Ishraqi) philosophy of Shihabuddin Suhrawardi (al-Maqtul). Nizamuddin Auliya, Ibn al-Arabi and Bayazid Bistami are not its originators." },
    "126": { correct: "a", correctText: "Munis al Arwah", exp: "Jahanara’s biography of Shaikh Muinuddin Chishti is titled Munis al-Arwah (“The Confidant of Spirits”). Fawaid ul Fuwad is by Amir Hasan Sijzi; the others are different works." },
    "127": { correct: "b", correctText: "Central Afghanistan", exp: "The town of Chisht (after which the Chishti silsila is named) is in central Afghanistan (near Herat). It is not in Turkey, Iran or Iraq." },
    "128": { correct: "a", correctText: "Vasugupta", exp: "Kashmir Shaivism (the Pratyabhijna/Trika system) was propounded by Vasugupta, author of the Shiva Sutras. Abhinavagupta was a later great exponent, not the founder." },
    "129": { correct: "c", correctText: "Bengali", exp: "Chandimangala (by Mukundaram Chakravarti) was composed in Bengali in the 16th century. It is not in Sanskrit, Tamil or Oriya." },
    "130": { correct: "a", correctText: "A-4 B-3 C-2 D-1", exp: "Brindavan Das → Chaitanyamangal (4), Krishnadas Kaviraj → Chaitanyacharitamrita (3), Mukundaram Chakravarti → Chandimangal (2), Rameshwar Bhattacharya → Shivasankirttan (1). (Options a and b are printed identically; the correct code is A-4 B-3 C-2 D-1.)" },
    "131": { correct: "a", correctText: "Basavanna", exp: "Basavanna (Basaveshwara) founded the Virashaiva (Lingayat) movement in 12th-century Karnataka. Sambandar, Appar and Sundarar were Tamil Nayanar saints." },
    "132": { correct: "c", correctText: "1, 2 and 3", exp: "Shankardeva’s teachings are known as Bhagavati/Eka-Sarana dharma (1); he promoted satras and namghars (2); and his works include the Kirtana-ghosha (3). All three are correct." },
    "133": { correct: "b", correctText: "2", exp: "Two statements are correct: Namdev helped transmit southern Bhakti to the north (1) and was a monotheist who opposed caste (2). Statement 3 is wrong — Namdev predates Kabir and was not his follower. So two are correct." },
    "134": { correct: "b", correctText: "1, 2 and 3", exp: "Virashaivism traces its origin to five teachers (1), its philosophy is Shaktivishishtadvaita (2), and the Ashtavarana are its eight observances (3). All three statements are correct." },
    "135": { correct: "b", correctText: "Shivsankirttan", exp: "The early-18th-century Bengali poet Rameshwar Bhattacharya wrote Shivsankirttan (Shivayan). Dharmamangal, Mansimha and Vidyasundar are different works/authors." },
    "136": { correct: "d", correctText: "Buddhism", exp: "The Sahajiya cult (10th–11th centuries) has its roots in Buddhist Tantra (Sahajayana). It is associated with Buddhism rather than early Bhakti, Sufism or Upanishadic philosophy." },
    "137": { correct: "a", correctText: "Mahanavami Dibba", exp: "The Mahanavami Dibba was the great ritual platform used by Vijayanagara kings (associated with the Mahanavami/Dussehra festival). The Lotus Mahal and Hazara Rama were other structures; Virupaksha is a temple." },
    "138": { correct: "d", correctText: "Military Commanders", exp: "The Amar-Nayakas of Vijayanagara were military commanders granted territories (amaram) to govern and from which to collect revenue. They were not village chieftains or civil servants." },
    "139": { correct: "d", correctText: "Vijayanagara", exp: "The Amara-Nayaka system was a key political innovation of the Vijayanagara Empire. It was not a Chola, Chalukya or Gupta system." },
    "140": { correct: "a", correctText: "Amuktamalyada", exp: "Krishnadevaraya composed the Amuktamalyada, a work on statecraft (and devotion), in Telugu. Jambavati Kalyanam is his Sanskrit work; Rayavachakamu is a later prose work." },
    "141": { correct: "d", correctText: "Telugu", exp: "The Amuktamalyada was written in Telugu by Krishnadevaraya. It is not in Sanskrit, Tamil or Kannada." },
    "142": { correct: "d", correctText: "Siddheshvara", exp: "Among Krishnadevaraya’s Ashtadiggajas (court poets) were Timmana, Dhurjati and Mallana. Siddheshvara was not one of his court poets." },
    "143": { correct: "d", correctText: "They were not allowed to use their share of revenue for the maintenance of temples", exp: "This statement is incorrect — the Amara-Nayakas DID use revenue to maintain temples and irrigation works. The other statements (a political innovation, military commanders collecting taxes, retaining revenue for contingents) are correct." },
    "144": { correct: "c", correctText: "1, 2 and 3", exp: "Gajapati = a powerful dynasty of Orissa (1), Ashvapati = the Deccan (Bahmani) Sultans (2), Narapati = the Rayas of Vijayanagara (3). All three pairs are correctly matched." },
    "145": { correct: "b", correctText: "Vijayanagara", exp: "The Portuguese traveller Domingo Paes described the city of Vijayanagara (Hampi) in glowing terms. He did not describe Madurai, Arikamedu or Gingee." },
    "146": { correct: "a", correctText: "Fortifications of Calicut", exp: "Abdur Razzaq, the Persian ambassador, was greatly impressed by the fortifications of Calicut (he mentioned its lines of forts) (verified). He was not specifically struck by its climate, spices or music in this context." },
    "147": { correct: "a", correctText: "Both true and II is the correct explanation of I", exp: "Pahi-kashta peasants were non-resident, contractual cultivators (I), and they worked either under the temptation of favourable terms or the compulsion of distress (II). Statement II explains why they cultivated on a contractual basis, so it correctly explains I." },
    "148": { correct: "b", correctText: "Both true but II is not the correct explanation of I", exp: "Zamindars were an exploitative class (I), yet they often received peasant support in agrarian uprisings (II). Both are true, but II (peasant support) does not explain I (their exploitative character); the two are contrasting facts. Hence II is not the explanation." },
    "149": { correct: "b", correctText: "Documents belonging to the Village Panchayats of Rajasthan, Gujarat and Maharashtra", exp: "Records of these village panchayats tell us about women protesting infidelity or neglect by the male household head. The Kitab-ul-Hind, Mandor sculptures and Ain-i-Akbari do not provide this specific information." },
    "150": { correct: "a", correctText: "Francisco Pelsaert", exp: "The Dutch factor Francisco Pelsaert (in his Remonstrantie) described the grinding poverty of Mughal peasants — “so much is wrung from the peasants…”. Bernier, Tavernier and Manucci made other observations." },
    "151": { correct: "c", correctText: "1, 2 and 3 only", exp: "Raiyat (1), Asami (2) and Muzarian (3) were Indo-Persian terms for a peasant. Majur (4) meant a labourer/wage worker, not a peasant. Hence 1, 2 and 3 only." },
    "152": { correct: "a", correctText: "Textile production", exp: "The Dadni system involved advance payments to weavers/artisans for textile (cloth) production. It was not about warfare, payment to officials or revenue collection." },
    "153": { correct: "c", correctText: "use of gypsum and lime mortars in making the inner surfaces of indigo vats water-proof", exp: "Indigo extraction improved when gypsum and lime mortars were used to make the inner surfaces of the vats waterproof, preventing leakage. The other options (fertilizer, mechanical crushing, slave labour) were not the improvement." },
    "154": { correct: "d", correctText: "1, 2 and 3", exp: "Zat rank indicated a mansabdar’s status and salary (1), Sawar rank the number of horsemen to be maintained (2), and high-ranking mansabdars (around 1000+) were designated nobles/Umara (3). The statements are taken together as correct. (Strictly the noble threshold is based on zat rank; the question treats statement 3 as correct.)" },
    "155": { correct: "a", correctText: "Arif Qandahari", exp: "The Tarikh-i-Akbari (an important source for Akbar’s reign) was written by Arif Qandahari. Bayazid Bayat, Badauni and Nizamuddin Ahmad wrote other histories of the period." },
    "156": { correct: "b", correctText: "Jahangir", exp: "The aristocrat Muqarrab Khan was a great favourite of Emperor Jahangir. He was not specially favoured by Akbar, Farrukhsiyar or Shah Alam." },
    "157": { correct: "b", correctText: "Church", exp: "Akbar’s 1598 farman permitted the Jesuit fathers (Padris) to build a church (house of prayer) in Cambay (Khambat), Gujarat (verified from the farman text). It did not authorise a temple, synagogue or Jain upashraya." },
    "158": { correct: "a", correctText: "Ayurveda", exp: "Among the “Indian sciences” the Ain-i Akbari lists as prescribed by Akbar for scholars to learn was Ayurveda (medicine) (verified). Vyakarana, Ganita and Jyotisha are not the keyed answer here." },
    "159": { correct: "a", correctText: "Ayurveda", exp: "This is the repeated question; the answer is again Ayurveda, listed in the Ain-i Akbari among the Indian sciences prescribed by Akbar (verified)." },
    "160": { correct: "a", correctText: "Raja Man Singh of Gwalior", exp: "‘Man Kautuhal’, a treatise on music, was prepared under the patronage of Raja Man Singh Tomar of Gwalior (a great patron of Dhrupad). It was not under Tansen, Meera Bai or Amir Khusrau." },
    "161": { correct: "d", correctText: "Bihzad", exp: "Mir Sayyid Ali, Maulana Dost Musawir (Abd al-Samad’s circle) and Maulana Yusuf were associated with Humayun’s atelier. Bihzad was the earlier Herat master and was not part of Humayun’s painters." },
    "162": { correct: "b", correctText: "Faizi", exp: "Faizi translated Bhaskaracharya’s Lilavati (mathematics) into Persian at Akbar’s court. Abul Fazl, Fathullah Shirazi and Ataullah Rashidi did not make this translation." },
    "163": { correct: "c", correctText: "Both 1 and 2", exp: "Sawai Jai Singh obtained de La Hire’s tables and reproduced a refraction table (1), and his astronomers used telescopes (including ones they made) to observe the phases of Venus (2). Both statements are accepted as correct." },
    "164": { correct: "b", correctText: "2", exp: "Two statements are correct: Tibb-i-Yunani was almost identical to contemporary Persian medicine (1) and Bernier explained Harvey’s circulation of blood to a noble (2). Statement 3 (smallpox inoculation described in classical Yunani/Ayurvedic texts) is not well-attested. So two are correct." },
    "165": { correct: "b", correctText: "Manucci", exp: "Niccolao Manucci never returned to Europe and settled down in India (dying at Madras/Pondicherry). Barbosa, Tavernier and Bernier returned to Europe." },
    "166": { correct: "a", correctText: "brick and mud (flagged — verify)", exp: "According to Tavernier, most 17th-century houses in Varanasi were built of brick and mud (only the wealthy used finer materials). (This detail is uncertain in the available sources; please cross-check the official key.)" },
    "167": { correct: "d", correctText: "Abbe J. A. Dubois", exp: "The observation that “a Hindu woman can go anywhere alone… and need never fear…” is attributed to Abbe J.A. Dubois. It was not made by Bernier, Tavernier or Thomas Roe." },
    "168": { correct: "d", correctText: "Prince Dara Shikoh", exp: "François Bernier was physician to Prince Dara Shikoh (and later attached to the noble Danishmand Khan). He was not physician to Murad, Jahanara or Shah Jahan." },
    "169": { correct: "a", correctText: "Arabic", exp: "Al-Biruni wrote his Kitab-ul-Hind (Tahqiq-i-Hind) in Arabic. It was not written in Persian, Urdu or Turkish." },
    "170": { correct: "a", correctText: "They brought Jahandar Shah to power.", exp: "This is not true — the Sayyid brothers brought Farrukhsiyar to power (defeating Jahandar Shah), not Jahandar Shah. Their administrative power, tolerant policy (abolishing jizya) and agreement with Shahu are correct." },
    "171": { correct: "d", correctText: "Nawab Saadat Khan", exp: "Saadat Khan (Burhan-ul-Mulk) was the first Nawab of Awadh, founding the dynasty in 1722. (Safdarjung later held the imperial Wazir title.) Among the options, Saadat Khan is the founder-Nawab." },
    "172": { correct: "a", correctText: "Babur", exp: "Babur was a follower of the Naqshbandi Sufi leader Khwaja Ubaydullah Ahrar. Humayun, Akbar and Jahangir are not specifically identified with Ahrar’s discipleship." },
    "173": { correct: "b", correctText: "A category of tenancy tenure under the Maratha rule", exp: "“Upari” referred to a temporary/non-hereditary cultivator (tenant) under Maratha land tenure, as opposed to the hereditary Mirasdar. It was not a Mughal tenure, a soldier or a headman." },
    "174": { correct: "a", correctText: "Baji Rao II", exp: "The Treaty of Bassein (31 December 1802) was signed by the Peshwa Baji Rao II with the British (a subsidiary alliance). Daulat Rao Sindhia and the others did not sign it." },
    "175": { correct: "a", correctText: "4-2-3-1", exp: "Earliest first: Treaty of Surat (1775, 4) → Treaty of Purandar (1776, 2) → Convention of Wadgaon (1779, 3) → Treaty of Salbai (1782, 1). This is 4, 2, 3, 1." },
    "176": { correct: "d", correctText: "Treaty of Salbai", exp: "The First Anglo-Maratha War was concluded by the Treaty of Salbai (1782). The Treaties of Surat and Purandar and the Convention of Wadgaon were earlier episodes in the conflict." },
    "177": { correct: "a", correctText: "2, 4, 1, 3", exp: "Chronologically: Capture of Torna (1646, 2) → Annexation of Javli (1656, 4) → Attack on Afzal Khan (1659, 1) → Attack on Shaista Khan (1663, 3). This is 2, 4, 1, 3." },
    "178": { correct: "c", correctText: "Both 1 and 2", exp: "The Ashta Pradhan scheme with defined duties was completed/announced at Shivaji’s coronation (1), and he replaced Persian with Marathi, coining Sanskrit administrative terms (2). Both statements are correct." },
    "179": { correct: "c", correctText: "1 and 3 only", exp: "Balutedars were village servants and artisans (1) found in the medieval Deccan/Maharashtra (3). Statement 2 is wrong — they served the whole village community, not individual peasant families. Hence 1 and 3 only." },
    "180": { correct: "d", correctText: "Both statements 1 and 2 are correct (printed options appear garbled — see note)", exp: "Shivaji sent an ambassador to Bombay seeking English aid against the Siddis of Danda-Rajpuri (1) and wanted grenades, mortars and ammunition (2) — both correct. The options as printed reference a non-existent “statement 3”; the intended answer is that both statements are correct." },
    "181": { correct: "d", correctText: "Colachel", exp: "Marthanda Varma of Travancore defeated the Dutch at the Battle of Colachel (1741). Wandiwash, Rakshasi-Tangadi and Pullalur were different battles." },
    "182": { correct: "b", correctText: "Battle of Colachel", exp: "The Travancore king (Marthanda Varma) defeated the Dutch in 1741 at the Battle of Colachel. The other battles listed are unrelated to this Dutch defeat." },
    "183": { correct: "c", correctText: "Both 1 and 2", exp: "Avantivarman, founder of the Utpala dynasty of Kashmir, focused on his subjects’ economic upliftment (1), and his minister Suyya’s engineering works greatly increased grain output and lowered prices (2). Both statements are correct." },
    "184": { correct: "c", correctText: "Shrivara", exp: "Shrivara composed Zainavilas (Jaina-Rajatarangini), a history of Kashmir’s rulers, during the reign of Zainul Abidin (verified). He continued the chronicle begun by his teacher Jonaraja." },
    "185": { correct: "c", correctText: "Ahoms", exp: "The Ahoms of Assam were famous for their metal-casting skills and cast excellent matchlocks (firearms) (verified). The Marathas, Rajputs and Gonds were not specifically noted for this." },
    "186": { correct: "a", correctText: "1, 2 and 3", exp: "Rana Kumbha of Mewar wrote a commentary on Jayadeva’s Gita Govinda (1), authored dramas using provincial languages (2), and erected the Kirti Stambha (Tower of Victory) at Chittor (3). All three statements are correct." },
    "187": { correct: "a", correctText: "Kakatiya", exp: "The titles ‘Rayagajakesari’ and ‘Dayagajakesari’ were associated with the Kakatiya dynasty (verified) — Daya-gaja-kesari with Prataparudra and Raya-gaja-kesari with Rudrama Devi. Not Vijayanagara, Gajapati or Rashtrakuta." },
    "188": { correct: "d", correctText: "Kakkuka", exp: "The Gwalior Prashasti (eulogy) of the Pratihara king Mihira Bhoja was composed by Kakkuka (verified). Nagabhata, Vatsaraja and Baladitya were not its author." },
    "189": { correct: "a", correctText: "1, 2 and 3", exp: "In Sanskrit texts/inscriptions (8th–14th c.), Muslims were denoted by Turushka (1, Turks), Tajika (2, Arabs) and Parashika (3, Persians). Kardamaka (4) was a Saka/Western-Kshatrapa lineage, not a term for Muslims. Hence 1, 2 and 3." },
    "190": { correct: "c", correctText: "Both 1 and 2", exp: "Apabhramsha appeared in recognizable forms by the 6th century (1) and developed from a mixture of regional vernaculars with the Prakrits and Sanskrit (2). Both statements are correct." },
    "191": { correct: "b", correctText: "Narayana Bhatta", exp: "The 16th-century Sanskrit text Vraja Bhakti Vilasa, on the Braj region, was authored by Narayana Bhatta (Narayan Bhatt of Vrindavan). It was not by Todar Mal, Chaitanya or Rupa Goswami." },
    "192": { correct: "c", correctText: "Guilds of Indian merchants", exp: "Manigramam and Nanadesi were powerful guilds (associations) of merchants in early medieval South India who carried on inland and maritime trade. They were not village groups or literary societies." },
    "193": { correct: "b", correctText: "Catapult", exp: "A munjaniq (manjaniq) was a stone-throwing siege engine — a catapult/mangonel. It was not a cannon, gun carriage or portable armoury." },
    "194": { correct: "c", correctText: "Both 1 and 2", exp: "The iron stirrup let an armoured warrior sit firmly without falling (1) and allowed a cavalry charge with lances held tight to the body without the rider being thrown off (2). Both statements are correct." },
    "195": { correct: "d", correctText: "A device for throwing stones (mangonel)", exp: "The manjaniq was a stone-throwing military device — a mangonel. It was not a gun-loading device, a cavalry technique or a gate-bolting device." },
    "196": { correct: "c", correctText: "3 (all three statements are correct)", exp: "The Konark horse (c. 1250) shows a ring-stirrup (1), a broad wooden stirrup appears at Khajuraho (c. 10th c.) (2), and iron stirrups were used in the Delhi Sultans’ armies from the 13th century (3). All three are correct." },
    "197": { correct: "c", correctText: "1 and 2 only (flagged)", exp: "The Katapayadi numeral system (Vararuchi) was used to compute the Moon’s position (1) and Achyuta Pisharati wrote Uparagakriyakrama on eclipses (2). Statement 3 (Ravi Varma’s observatory and the Kollam era) is doubtful. Hence 1 and 2 only. (Statement 3 is debatable; verify with the official key.)" },
    "198": { correct: "c", correctText: "1 and 2 only", exp: "Raja Ram Mohan Roy founded the Atmiya Sabha (1) and the Brahmo Samaj (2). The Prarthana Samaj (Atmaram Pandurang) and Arya Samaj (Dayananda) were founded by others. Hence 1 and 2 only." },
    "199": { correct: "a", correctText: "1 and 2 only", exp: "The Arya Samaj’s base was mainly in Punjab and western UP (1) and comprised largely trading castes (2). Statement 3 is wrong — its base was actually wider than the Brahmo Samaj. Hence 1 and 2 only." },
    "200": { correct: "c", correctText: "Tarabai Shinde", exp: "Tarabai Shinde authored “Stri Purush Tulana” (A Comparison between Women and Men), a pioneering feminist critique. Pandita Ramabai, Sarojini Naidu and Rameshwari Nehru did not write it." },
    "201": { correct: "d", correctText: "K. N. Natarajan", exp: "The “Indian Social Reformer” (started 1890) was edited by K. Natarajan (with Ranade’s inspiration). Telang, Veeresalingam and Chandavarkar were not its editor." },
    "202": { correct: "d", correctText: "1 and 4", exp: "Sir Syed saw India as a federation of ethnic communities of common descent (1), and the MAO College blended Muslim theology with European empiricism (4). His philosophy was not similar to the INC’s (2), nor did he imagine India as a nation-state of individual citizens (3). Hence 1 and 4." },
    "203": { correct: "a", correctText: "Her Holiness Mataji Maharani Tapaswini", exp: "The Mahakali Pathshala in Calcutta was founded by Mataji Maharani Tapaswini. Sister Nivedita, Madame Blavatsky and Sarojini Naidu were not its founder." },
    "204": { correct: "d", correctText: "Hindu Mahasabha", exp: "The (Akhil Bharatiya) Hindu Mahasabha had its origins at the Haridwar Kumbh Mela of 1915. The Sanatan Dharma Sabha, Dev Samaj and Brahmin Sabha were not started there in 1915." },
    "205": { correct: "a", correctText: "Devendranath Tagore in 1839", exp: "The Tattvabodhini Sabha was established by Devendranath Tagore in 1839 (to propagate Brahmo ideas). The other names/years are incorrect." },
    "206": { correct: "a", correctText: "Hridayanath Kunzru", exp: "Hridayanath Kunzru (of the Servants of India Society) founded the Seva Samiti at Allahabad in 1914. Gokhale, Shri Ram Bajpai and T.B. Sapru were not its founder." },
    "207": { correct: "d", correctText: "Gurdaspur", exp: "The Ahmadiyya movement was started by Mirza Ghulam Ahmad at Qadian, in Gurdaspur district, Punjab. Not at Patna, Aligarh or Bhopal." },
    "208": { correct: "d", correctText: "Shri Ram Bajpai", exp: "The Seva Samiti Boy Scouts Association (1914) was formed by Shri Ram Bajpai (with Kunzru’s Seva Samiti). The other names are not credited with founding the Scouts association." },
    "209": { correct: "d", correctText: "G.H. Deshmukh", exp: "Gopal Hari Deshmukh (“Lokahitwadi”) wrote the Shatapatre (Satapatra) series of 100 reformist letters in the 19th century. Ranade, Tilak and Bankim did not author it." },
    "210": { correct: "a", correctText: "Gopal Hari Deshmukh", exp: "Gopal Hari Deshmukh was popularly known as “Lokahitwadi” (well-wisher of the people). Ranade, Gokhale and Phule had other titles." },
    "211": { correct: "b", correctText: "Vedas", exp: "Swami Dayananda Saraswati took inspiration from the Vedas, giving the call “Back to the Vedas.” He did not base his reform on the Puranas, medieval saints or Sufism." },
    "212": { correct: "b", correctText: "Hriday Nath Kunzru", exp: "Hriday Nath Kunzru, a member of the Servants of India Society, founded the Seva Samiti at Allahabad in 1914. The others are not credited as its founder." },
    "213": { correct: "a", correctText: "Radhakanta Deb", exp: "Radhakanta Deb founded the Dharma Sabha (Hindu Dharma Sabha) in 1830 to oppose social reforms like the abolition of sati. Ram Mohan Roy and the Tagores were reformers on the other side." },
    "214": { correct: "b", correctText: "2, 3 and 4", exp: "The SGPC was formed in 1920 as part of the Akali movement (2), to reclaim Sikh shrines from government-backed committees (3), and it formed the Akali Dal to coordinate jathas (4). Statement 1 is wrong — it was not a 19th-century political wing. Hence 2, 3 and 4." },
    "215": { correct: "b", correctText: "Both true & II not explanation", exp: "Non-cooperation in Punjab began with the student movement inspired by Lala Lajpat Rai (I), and the Sikh countryside was stirred by the Akali upsurge (II). Both are true, but the Akali upsurge does not explain the student movement, so II is not the explanation." },
    "216": { correct: "a", correctText: "Guru Nanak", exp: "Guru Nanak instituted the sangat (congregational worship) and the practice of collective recitation/community fellowship. The later Gurus developed it further, but its origin is credited to Guru Nanak." },
    "217": { correct: "b", correctText: "Abanindranath Tagore", exp: "Abanindranath Tagore (with E.B. Havell and the Tagore circle) was a founder of the Indian Society of Oriental Art (1907). Dwarakanath and Bankim Chandra were not involved." },
    "218": { correct: "c", correctText: "1, 2 and 3 only", exp: "The “Serampore Trio” were William Carey (1), Joshua Marshman (2) and William Ward (3). David Hare (4) was associated with the Hindu College/Calcutta education, not the Serampore Mission. Hence 1, 2 and 3 only." },
    "219": { correct: "d", correctText: "Gopal Krishna Gokhale", exp: "In 1911 Gopal Krishna Gokhale introduced a bill in the Imperial Legislative Council for compulsory, free primary education. The other leaders did not introduce this bill." },
    "220": { correct: "b", correctText: "Annie Besant", exp: "Annie Besant founded the Central Hindu School at Benaras, which later developed into the Banaras Hindu University (with Madan Mohan Malaviya). The school itself was Besant’s foundation." },
    "221": { correct: "d", correctText: "1, 2 and 3", exp: "Sawai Jai Singh of Amber promoted widow remarriage (1), the Maratha general Parshuram Bhau also promoted it (2), and Ram Mohan Roy opposed sati (3). All three statements are correct." },
    "222": { correct: "d", correctText: "She was honoured with Bharat Ratna in 1956", exp: "This is incorrect — Dr. Muthulakshmi Reddy received the Padma Bhushan (1956), not the Bharat Ratna. She was indeed the first girl in a men’s college, the first woman legislator in British India, and a medical professional." },
    "223": { correct: "a", correctText: "1", exp: "Only one statement is correct — Sarojini Naidu led a delegation to London demanding female franchise (3). Statement 1 is wrong (“A Comparison Between Women and Men” was by Tarabai Shinde, not Pandita Ramabai), and statement 2 is wrong (Tarabai Shinde was a writer, not a medical worker). Hence 1." },
    "224": { correct: "a", correctText: "Binodini Dasi", exp: "The Bengali actress Binodini Dasi serialised her autobiography ‘Amar Katha’ (1910–1913). Rashsundari Debi wrote ‘Amar Jiban’; Begum Rokeya and Kailashbashini Debi wrote other works." },
    "225": { correct: "d", correctText: "1870", exp: "The Poona Sarvajanik Sabha was established in 1870 (by M.G. Ranade and others). The other years are incorrect." },
    "226": { correct: "a", correctText: "1, 2, 3, 4", exp: "Earliest first: Poona Sarvajanik Sabha (1870, 1) → Indian Association (1876, 2) → Madras Mahajan Sabha (1884, 3) → Bombay Presidency Association (1885, 4). This is 1, 2, 3, 4." },
    "227": { correct: "c", correctText: "All", exp: "Ferozeshah Mehta and Badruddin Tyabji formed the Bombay Presidency Association (1); Surendranath Banerjee planned the Indian National Conference at Calcutta (2); and A.O. Hume created an all-India body (the INC) partly to channel grievances (3). All three are taken as correct." },
    "228": { correct: "c", correctText: "Extension of Permanent Settlement", exp: "Moderates did not demand extension of the Permanent Settlement (they sought relief from heavy land revenue). They did demand repeal of the Arms Act, more Indians in higher/army jobs, etc. Hence this is the non-moderate demand." },
    "229": { correct: "a", correctText: "Overthrow of alien rule", exp: "The moderates sought reforms within the British system, not the overthrow of alien rule. Their methods were constitutional agitation, slow orderly progress and mobilisation of public opinion." },
    "230": { correct: "a", correctText: "Lokmanya Tilak", exp: "Bal Gangadhar Tilak founded the Marathi newspaper Kesari (and the English Mahratta). Patel, Lala Lajpat Rai and Gandhi did not found Kesari." },
    "231": { correct: "d", correctText: "Voice of… (the mismatched pair; option text cut off in file)", exp: "Navjivan–Gandhi, Mahratta–Tilak and Bengalee–Surendranath Banerjea are correctly matched. The fourth pair (“Voice of India…”) is the incorrectly matched one. (The full text of option (d) is truncated in the uploaded file.)" },
    "232": { correct: "b", correctText: "Michael Madhusudan Dutta", exp: "Neel Darpan (by Dinabandhu Mitra) was translated into English by Michael Madhusudan Dutta (verified); it was published by Rev. James Long, who was prosecuted for it. So the translator is Michael Madhusudan Dutta." },
    "233": { correct: "c", correctText: "Anandamath", exp: "Bankim Chandra Chattopadhyay’s Anandamath portrays the Mother Goddess in three images (as she was, as she is, as she will be) and contains ‘Vande Mataram’. The other novels do not present this triple image." },
    "234": { correct: "b", correctText: "Maulavi Ahmadullah Shah", exp: "Maulavi Ahmadullah Shah of Faizabad was known during 1857 as “Danka Shah” (the one with the drum). Shah Mal, Nana Sahib and Tantia Tope were other 1857 leaders." },
    "235": { correct: "b", correctText: "Agra (option (d) truncated in file — see note)", exp: "Among the major 1857 centres, Delhi and Ayodhya/Awadh were active, whereas Agra was not a principal rebel centre (Europeans took refuge in Agra Fort). The fourth option is cut off in the file; based on the visible options, Agra is the town not a centre of the Revolt. Verify against the original." },
    "236": { correct: "d", correctText: "1, 2 and 4", exp: "The Deccan Riots led to the Deccan Agriculturalists’ Relief Act 1879 (1), did not spread across all Maharashtra due to suppression (2), and were rooted in the cotton-boom impoverishment after the American Civil War (4). Statement 3 (riots spread throughout) is wrong. Hence 1, 2 and 4." },
    "237": { correct: "a", correctText: "Phulaguri Dhawa (1861)", exp: "The Phulaguri Dhawa (Assam, 1861) arose out of the British opium (and tax) policy. The Birsaite Ulgulan, Pabna Revolt and Maratha (Deccan) uprising had other causes." },
    "238": { correct: "a", correctText: "Santals", exp: "The British created the Damin-i-Koh (a demarcated forest tract in the Rajmahal hills) to settle the Santals. It was not created for the Mundas, Oraons or Saoras." },
    "239": { correct: "b", correctText: "Madari Pasi", exp: "The Eka (Unity) Movement in Awadh (1921–22) was taken over by Madari Pasi, who steered it away from Congress control. Baba Ramchandra led the earlier Awadh Kisan movement." },
    "240": { correct: "d", correctText: "I false, II true", exp: "Statement I is false — the Oudh Kisan Sabha (1920) actually brought hundreds of kisan sabhas under its wing. Statement II is true — it asked kisans to refuse to till bedakhli land and not to offer hari and begar. Hence I false, II true." },
    "241": { correct: "b", correctText: "1, 2 and 3", exp: "Warren Hastings faced the Sanyasi-Faqir disturbances in Bengal/Bihar (1); there were armed Shaivite Naga sanyasi bands (2); and Majnu Shah led bands into Bengal from 1771 (3). All three are correct." },
    "242": { correct: "c", correctText: "Both 1 and 2", exp: "19th-century peasants did revolt against moneylenders and grain dealers (1), and at Supa (Poona) in May 1875 they attacked shopkeepers and burnt the bahi-khatas (account books) (2). Both statements are correct." },
    "243": { correct: "b", correctText: "Monotheism and internal social reform", exp: "The Kherwar/Sapha Har movement (1870s, among the Santals) preached monotheism and internal social reform. It did not preach acceptance of the Hindu pantheon, Yoga-Mimamsa or polytheism." },
    "244": { correct: "a", correctText: "The Rampa Rebellion, 1879-1880", exp: "In the Rampa Rebellion of 1879–80, the Koya and Konda tribal chiefs rose against a local overlord (a mansabdar family). This is distinct from the later Rampa (1922-24) and Gudem uprisings." },
    "245": { correct: "d", correctText: "1, 2 and 3", exp: "For Gandhi, Swaraj was linked with Ahimsa and Satyagraha (1), had political and beyond-political senses (2), and required time and patience (3). Statement 4 (obtained easily and quickly) contradicts Gandhi’s view. Hence 1, 2 and 3." },
    "246": { correct: "a", correctText: "1 and 2 only", exp: "Gandhi was influenced by the Pranami sect (unity of faiths) (1) and by the theosophists (2). The claim that he was an admirer of Romantics like Wordsworth (3) is not a recognised formative influence. Hence 1 and 2 only." },
    "247": { correct: "c", correctText: "1, 2 and 3 only", exp: "In his BHU speech Gandhi charged the elite with neglecting the poor (1), said salvation lay through the farmers (2), and highlighted the plight of untouchables (3). Statement 4 (championing Ahmedabad mill owners) is wrong. Hence 1, 2 and 3." },
    "248": { correct: "c", correctText: "Mahatma Gandhi", exp: "The statement on the sound body being a ready instrument of the spirit is attributed to Mahatma Gandhi (reflecting his views on health/discipline). Not to Patel, Churchill or Baden-Powell." },
    "249": { correct: "a", correctText: "Mahatma Gandhi", exp: "Gandhi founded the Phoenix Settlement (1904, near Durban, South Africa). Ambedkar, Tagore and Vivekananda were not its founders." },
    "250": { correct: "d", correctText: "South India", exp: "During his 1921 tour of South India (at Madurai), Gandhi shaved his head and adopted the loincloth to identify with the poor. It was not during the Ahmedabad, Champaran or Chauri Chaura events." },
    "251": { correct: "b", correctText: "sodium chloride", exp: "The Dandi March (Salt Satyagraha, 1930) was associated with salt — sodium chloride. Gandhi broke the salt law by making salt from seawater at Dandi." },
    "252": { correct: "d", correctText: "Congress agreed to take part in the Second Round Table Conference", exp: "Under the Gandhi-Irwin Pact (1931), the Congress agreed to suspend the Civil Disobedience Movement and participate in the Second Round Table Conference. The other statements about prisoner release are incorrectly framed." },
    "253": { correct: "c", correctText: "Inauguration of Banaras Hindu University 1916", exp: "Gandhi’s first major public appearance in India was his speech at the inauguration of BHU in 1916. Champaran (1917), Kheda (1918) and Rowlatt (1919) came later." },
    "254": { correct: "c", correctText: "M.K. Gandhi", exp: "Gandhi suggested dissolving the Congress as a political body and replacing it with a Lok Sevak Sangh (in his last writings, 1948). Patel, Ambedkar and Nehru did not make this suggestion." },
    "255": { correct: "a", correctText: "Kamaladevi Chattopadhyay", exp: "The socialist activist Kamaladevi Chattopadhyay persuaded Gandhi not to restrict the salt-march protest to men alone. Sarojini Naidu, Matangini Hazra and Mithuben Petit participated but did not make this specific persuasion." },
    "256": { correct: "b", correctText: "All India Congress Committee in 1921", exp: "The wide-scale distribution of charkhas (as part of the constructive/Non-Cooperation programme) was decided by the All India Congress Committee in 1921. The other options are incorrect." },
    "257": { correct: "c", correctText: "Taking control of the law and order machinery of the State by the Congress Working Committee", exp: "The Non-Cooperation programme involved boycott of schools/colleges, surrender of titles and building the Congress organisation — but NOT seizing the State’s law-and-order machinery. Hence option (c) was not part of the programme." },
    "258": { correct: "d", correctText: "Karnataka", exp: "The Sanikatta Salt Works, a site of salt satyagraha, is in Karnataka (Uttara Kannada). It is not in Gujarat, Tamil Nadu or Kerala." },
    "259": { correct: "a", correctText: "4, 3, 1, 2", exp: "Rowlatt Act = 1919 (4), Salt March = 1930 (3), Chauri Chaura = 1922 (1), Second Round Table Conference = 1931 (2). This gives A-4, B-3, C-1, D-2." },
    "260": { correct: "b", correctText: "2, 3 and 4", exp: "The Salt March was widely covered by the American/European press (2), saw large-scale women’s participation for the first time (3), and impressed on the British the need to devolve power (4). Statement 1 (ignored by European media) is wrong. Hence 2, 3 and 4." },
    "261": { correct: "d", correctText: "2 only", exp: "The Non-Cooperation Movement saw non-Brahmin lower-caste participation in Madras and Maharashtra (2, correct). Statement 4 is wrong (Gandhi withdrew the movement after Chauri Chaura), statement 3 is wrong (there was labour unrest), and statement 1 is not accurate. Hence 2 only." },
    "262": { correct: "c", correctText: "Germany", exp: "Subhas Chandra Bose started the Azad Hind Radio in Germany (Berlin, 1942). It was not in Japan, Austria or Malaysia." },
    "263": { correct: "c", correctText: "The Muslim League", exp: "The Muslim League formally accepted the Cabinet Mission Plan on 6 June 1946 (the plan having rejected a sovereign Pakistan). The Congress’s acceptance was partial/conditional and later." },
    "264": { correct: "a", correctText: "Sahajananda Saraswati", exp: "Swami Sahajanand Saraswati was elected President of the All India Kisan Sabha session held at Vijayawada in 1944 (verified). Vinoba Bhave, Achyut Patwardhan and Narendra Dev were not the elected president there." },
    "265": { correct: "b", correctText: "Sikandar Hayat Khan", exp: "The Punjab Unionist leader Sikandar Hayat Khan opposed “a Pakistan that would mean Muslim Raj here and Hindu Raj elsewhere.” It was not Ghaffar Khan, Azad or Kidwai." },
    "266": { correct: "d", correctText: "A Communist Party document… anti-imperialist people’s front", exp: "The Dutt-Bradley thesis (1936) was a Communist Party document holding that the National Congress could play a great, even foremost, part in an anti-imperialist people’s front. The other options are wrong." },
    "267": { correct: "b", correctText: "Ram Manohar Lohia", exp: "The concept of a “Four Pillar State” (decentralised polity, free from district magistracy) was advanced by Ram Manohar Lohia. Not by Lala Lajpat Rai, Ram Mohan Roy or Bose." },
    "268": { correct: "b", correctText: "Both true & II not explanation", exp: "The United Provinces became a strong Congress base during Non-Cooperation (I), and Bengal’s literary output during Non-Cooperation was meagre compared to the Swadeshi years (II). Both are true, but II does not explain I, so it is not the explanation." },
    "269": { correct: "c", correctText: "Lahore", exp: "Purna Swaraj (complete independence) was proclaimed at the Lahore Session of the Congress on 31 December 1929 (with 26 January 1930 as Independence Day). Not at Ahmedabad, Calcutta or Lucknow." },
    "270": { correct: "b", correctText: "Muslim League", exp: "Subhas Chandra Bose allied with the Muslim League in 1939–40 for the campaign to remove/destroy the Holwell Monument (the “Black Hole” memorial) in Calcutta. Not with the CPI, Hindu Mahasabha or Unionists." },
    "271": { correct: "a", correctText: "M.S. Aney (flagged — verify)", exp: "M.S. Aney is associated with moving the motion for the Secret Sitting Session of the (Central) Assembly in 1942. (This specific procedural detail is uncertain in available sources; please cross-check the official key.)" },
    "272": { correct: "d", correctText: "Sir Syed Ahmad Khan", exp: "The Mohammedan Anglo-Oriental Defence Association of Upper India (1893) was founded by Sir Syed Ahmad Khan (assisted by Theodore Beck) to defend Muslim political interests (verified). Beck assisted but was not the founder." },
    "273": { correct: "a", correctText: "Non-Cooperation Movement", exp: "The call to renounce all voluntary associations with the British Government (titles, schools, courts, councils) was given during the Non-Cooperation Movement (1920–22). Not during CDM, Quit India or the anti-partition agitation." },
    "274": { correct: "b", correctText: "2, 1, 3, 4", exp: "Chronologically: Champaran Satyagraha (1917, 2) → Ahmedabad Mill Strike (1918, 1) → Foundation of the Satyagraha Sabha (Feb 1919, 3) → Jallianwala Bagh Massacre (Apr 1919, 4). This is 2, 1, 3, 4." },
    "275": { correct: "d", correctText: "1, 2 and 3", exp: "The year 1916 saw the Lucknow Session of the Congress (1), the Congress-League (Lucknow) Pact (2) and the formation of the Home Rule Leagues (3). All three are correct." },
    "276": { correct: "c", correctText: "1, 2, 3, 4", exp: "Chronologically: Lucknow Pact (1916, 1) → Return of Subhas Chandra Bose to India (early 1920s, 2) → Cripps Mission (1942, 3) → Naval Mutiny in Bombay (1946, 4). This is 1, 2, 3, 4." },
    "277": { correct: "c", correctText: "1 and 4 only", exp: "At the Second RTC (1931) Britain refused the basic demand for freedom (1), and the Civil Disobedience Movement began with the breaking of salt laws (4). Statement 2 (dominion status in 1932) is wrong, and statement 3 (Willingdon’s reconciliation) is wrong (he was repressive). Hence 1 and 4 only." },
    "278": { correct: "b", correctText: "3, 2, 4, 1 (corrected sequence — see note)", exp: "Chronologically: Dandi March (April 1930, 3) → Gandhi-Irwin Pact (March 1931, 1) → Second RTC (Sept 1931, 4) → Muslim League Pakistan Resolution (1940, 2), i.e. 3, 1, 4, 2. None of the printed options exactly shows 3,1,4,2; the closest/intended order beginning with Dandi March is option (b)-type sequencing — verify the option lettering against the original paper." },
    "279": { correct: "d", correctText: "Satara", exp: "In 1943 young leaders in Satara district of Maharashtra set up a parallel government (prati sarkar) with seva dals and tufan dals. Not in Pune, Nasik or Nagpur." },
    "280": { correct: "b", correctText: "2 only", exp: "The question asks which is NOT correct. The Azamgarh Proclamation was a declaration by the rebels of 1857 (statement 1 is correct), so statement 2 (linking it to the 1942 underground movement) is the one that is not correct. Hence 2 only." },
    "281": { correct: "b", correctText: "Subhadra Kumari Chauhan", exp: "The famous poem “Khoob ladi mardani woh to Jhansi wali rani thi” was written by Subhadra Kumari Chauhan (“Jhansi ki Rani”). Not by Mahadevi Varma, Amrita Pritam or Balamani Amma." },
    "282": { correct: "c", correctText: "Both 1 and 2", exp: "Shah Mal mobilised the Baraut region and turned an Englishman’s bungalow into a “hall of justice” (1), and Gonoo was a Kol leader of the Singhbhum region of Chotanagpur (2). Both statements are correct." },
    "283": { correct: "a", correctText: "4-3-2-1", exp: "Kudi Arasu → E.V. Ramaswami Naicker (4), Kisan Bulletin → Indulal Yagnik (3), Bombay Chronicle → Pherozeshah Mehta (2), Bhawani Mandir → Aurobindo Ghosh (1). This gives 4, 3, 2, 1." },
    "284": { correct: "a", correctText: "Warren Hastings", exp: "Warren Hastings became the first Governor-General (of Bengal/Fort William) after the Regulating Act of 1773. Lord North was the British PM; Elphinstone and Francis held other posts." },
    "285": { correct: "a", correctText: "Morley-Minto Reforms, 1909", exp: "Separate electorates for Muslims were introduced by the Morley-Minto Reforms (Indian Councils Act) of 1909. The Communal Award (1932) extended separate electorates further, but they were first granted in 1909." },
    "286": { correct: "b", correctText: "Act of 1947 laid down the basic framework of the Indian Constitution", exp: "This statement is not correct — the Constitution’s framework was laid by the Constituent Assembly, not the Indian Independence Act 1947 (which provided for partition and two dominions). The other statements about the Act are correct." },
    "287": { correct: "d", correctText: "Quit India Movement", exp: "Matangini Hazra and Lakshman Naik sacrificed their lives during the Quit India Movement (1942). Not during the Bardoli Satyagraha, Non-Cooperation or Civil Disobedience movements." },
    "288": { correct: "d", correctText: "The British Government could enter into a separate constitutional arrangement with any of the acceding provinces", exp: "This is incorrect — the Cripps proposals allowed a separate arrangement with the non-acceding provinces (those rejecting the constitution), not the acceding ones. The other statements (sent March 1942; elected Constituent Assembly; provinces could retain their position) are correct." },
    "289": { correct: "d", correctText: "All four statements (1, 2, 3 and 4) are correct (printed options appear garbled — see note)", exp: "The Cabinet Mission (1946) came to negotiate transfer of power (1), proposed a federal plan with maximum regional autonomy (2), a federation of provinces and states with a federal centre (3), and provincial grouping/regional unions (4) — all correct (verified). The compilation’s options (“1 only / 1 and 2 / 2 and 3 / 3 and 4”) seem mis-transcribed; the original paper’s answer was “1, 2, 3 and 4.”" },
    "290": { correct: "b", correctText: "Subhas Chandra Bose", exp: "“The Indian Struggle 1920–1942” was written by Subhas Chandra Bose. Not by Savarkar, Patel or Sarat Chandra Bose." },
    "291": { correct: "c", correctText: "Both 1 and 2", exp: "After forming the INA, Bose recruited soldiers from Indian POWs in Japanese camps (1) and raised a women’s detachment, the Rani of Jhansi Regiment (2). Both statements are correct." },
    "292": { correct: "c", correctText: "Bhagwati Charan Vohra", exp: "“The Philosophy of the Bomb” (1930) was written by Bhagwati Charan Vohra (in response to Gandhi’s “The Cult of the Bomb”). Not by Sukhdev, Azad or Bhagat Singh directly." },
    "293": { correct: "d", correctText: "1, 2, 3 and 4", exp: "Bhagat Singh, Jatindranath, Ajoy Ghosh and Phanindranath Ghosh are all listed among the founder/member group of the HSRA, reorganised in September 1928 at Ferozeshah Kotla. Hence all four." },
    "294": { correct: "a", correctText: "San Francisco", exp: "The headquarters of the Ghadar Party/Movement was at San Francisco (the Yugantar Ashram). Not at Stanford, Portland or Florida." },
    "295": { correct: "d", correctText: "Sachindranath Sanyal", exp: "“Bandi Jivan” (A Life of Captivity) was written by the revolutionary Sachindranath Sanyal. Not by Rash Behari Bose, Savarkar or Aruna Asaf Ali." },
    "296": { correct: "d", correctText: "1, 2 and 3", exp: "The Ghadar Movement began in 1913 in San Francisco (1), was founded by Sohan Singh Bhakna (2), and took its name from the weekly newspaper Ghadar published in several Indian languages (3). All three are correct." },
    "297": { correct: "c", correctText: "T.B. Sapru and M.R. Jayakar", exp: "The National Liberal Federation (Liberal Party) was formed by moderates like Tej Bahadur Sapru and M.R. Jayakar (with Surendranath Banerjee). Motilal Nehru and C.R. Das were Swarajists." },
    "298": { correct: "b", correctText: "Vithalbhai Patel", exp: "Vithalbhai Patel belonged to the Swarajists (Pro-Changers), not the No-Changers. M.A. Ansari, Rajagopalachari and Kasturi Ranga Iyengar were among the No-Changers." },
    "299": { correct: "a", correctText: "Acharya Narendra Dev", exp: "Acharya Narendra Dev was a founder (and first president) of the Congress Socialist Party (1934). Jawaharlal and Motilal Nehru were not its founders." },
    "300": { correct: "c", correctText: "3, 2, 1", exp: "Earliest first: Satyashodhak Samaj (1873, 3) → Bardoli Satyagraha (1928, 2) → Chipko Movement (1973, 1). This is 3, 2, 1." },
    "301": { correct: "a", correctText: "Both true and II is the correct explanation of I", exp: "The communists split from the AITUC in 1931 (I), and by 1928 they had already diverged from the mainstream national movement (II). Their earlier divergence explains the 1931 split, so II is the correct explanation of I." },
    "302": { correct: "c", correctText: "N.M. Joshi", exp: "N.M. Joshi was a key founder of the All India Trade Union Congress (AITUC) in 1920 (Lala Lajpat Rai was its first president). B.P. Wadia, Dange and Ranadive were not its founder in this sense." },
    "303": { correct: "c", correctText: "Madras Labour Union", exp: "The Madras Labour Union (1918, founded by B.P. Wadia) was India’s first trade union in the proper sense. The other named “unions” were not the first." },
    "304": { correct: "a", correctText: "Sarala Devi Chaudhurani", exp: "Sarala Devi Chaudhurani was a nationalist/feminist (founder of Bharat Stree Mahamandal), not a labour-strike leader of the 1920s. Ushabai Dange, Prabhabati Devi and Anasuya Behn (Sarabhai) were labour organisers." },
    "305": { correct: "a", correctText: "Narayan Surve", exp: "The Marathi poet Narayan Surve wrote ‘Maze Vidyapeeth’ (My University), reflecting Bombay working-class life. Not Amol Palekar, Bhalchandra Nemade or Narendra Jadhav." },
    "306": { correct: "d", correctText: "1, 2 and 3", exp: "Annie Besant (1), Sarojini Naidu (2) and Hirabai (Herabai) Tata (3) gave evidence before the Joint Select Committee on the Government of India Bill 1919 in favour of female franchise. All three." },
    "307": { correct: "c", correctText: "1 and 3", exp: "The Ilbert Bill (1883) proposed limited criminal jurisdiction for Indian officials over Europeans (1), and it generated strong European opposition (3). It did not propose complete jurisdiction (2), and it was passed only after dilution (so 4 is wrong). Hence 1 and 3." },
    "308": { correct: "c", correctText: "1, 2 and 3", exp: "The Government of India Act 1858 transferred sovereignty from the Company to the Crown (1), was the first statute for direct British rule (2), and embodied absolute imperial control without popular participation (3). All three are correct." },
    "309": { correct: "a", correctText: "1 and 2 only", exp: "The Indian Councils Act 1861 added non-official members (a “grain” of popular element) (1) whose functions were confined to legislative proposals (2). Statement 3 is wrong — the Governor-General retained effective legislative power (veto/ordinance). Hence 1 and 2 only." },
    "310": { correct: "c", correctText: "1, 2 and 3", exp: "The Objectives Resolution inspired the Constitution through all its stages (1), was a declaration/pledge, not just a resolution (2), and provided its underlying philosophy (3). All three are correct." },
    "311": { correct: "a", correctText: "1 and 2 only", exp: "Alladi Krishnaswami Ayyar favoured the Supreme Court’s role in constitutional interpretation (1) and held it should balance liberty and social control (2). He did not believe in executive dominance over the judiciary (3) or dictatorial rule (4). Hence 1 and 2 only." },
    "312": { correct: "a", correctText: "4, 2, 1, 3", exp: "Chronologically: Cornwallis Code (1793, 4) → Vernacular Press Act (1878, 2) → Indian Factory Act (1881, 1) → Morley-Minto Reforms (1909, 3). This is 4, 2, 1, 3." },
    "313": { correct: "b", correctText: "Denied masters the use of Courts to assert their claims on slaves", exp: "Act V of 1843 (Indian Slavery Act) denied legal recognition to slavery — masters could not use the courts to enforce claims over slaves. It did not give masters rights or work jointly with them." },
    "314": { correct: "b", correctText: "1833", exp: "The East India Company lost its monopoly of the China (tea) trade under the Charter Act of 1833. (It had lost the India trade monopoly in 1813.)" },
    "315": { correct: "b", correctText: "It made the Central Executive responsible to the Legislature", exp: "This is not correct — the Government of India Act 1919 (Montagu-Chelmsford) did not make the central executive responsible to the legislature; dyarchy applied only at the provincial level. The other statements (communal representation, the name, federal separation of subjects) are correct." },
    "316": { correct: "d", correctText: "Government of India Act, 1935", exp: "The Government of India Act 1935 reserved seats for women in the legislatures in line with the communal allocation of seats. The earlier Acts did not do this." },
    "317": { correct: "c", correctText: "Government of India Act, 1935", exp: "The creation of a Federal Court in India was provided for by the Government of India Act 1935 (the Federal Court was set up in 1937). The 1919 Act and the Lee Commission did not establish it." },
    "318": { correct: "c", correctText: "1 and 3 only", exp: "In the 1937 provincial elections only ~10–12% of the population could vote (1), and the Congress won absolute majorities in five of eleven provinces (3). Statement 2 is wrong (untouchables had reserved-seat votes), and statement 4 is wrong (the Muslim League did poorly). Hence 1 and 3 only." },
    "319": { correct: "c", correctText: "S.B. Tambe", exp: "S.B. Tambe was the first to accept a ministerial position in the Central Provinces (October 1925), causing controversy among the Swarajists. Not Moonje, Jayakar or Sasmal." },
    "320": { correct: "a", correctText: "Punjab and Sind", exp: "In the 1937 elections the Congress was not the single largest party in Punjab (Unionist Party) and Sind. In Madras and Assam it fared much better. Hence Punjab and Sind." },
    "321": { correct: "d", correctText: "Karachi Session", exp: "The resolution on Fundamental Rights and the National Economic Programme was passed at the Karachi Session of the Congress (1931, presided by Sardar Patel). Not at Tripuri, Lahore or Lucknow." },
    "322": { correct: "c", correctText: "A-3 B-4 C-2 D-1", exp: "“Human beings possess dignity” → Immanuel Kant (3); “Swaraj when we learn to rule ourselves” → Mahatma Gandhi (4); “Freedom implies equal distribution of wealth” → Subhas Chandra Bose (2); “Real freedom is freedom from fear” → Aung San Suu Kyi (1). This gives A-3, B-4, C-2, D-1." },
    "323": { correct: "c", correctText: "1 and 2 only", exp: "The All India Census was first attempted in 1872 (1) and has been regularly undertaken since 1881 (2). Statement 3 is wrong — it is a decennial (ten-year), not five-year, exercise. Hence 1 and 2 only." },
    "324": { correct: "c", correctText: "Both 1 and 2", exp: "The first All India Census was attempted in 1872 (1), and from 1881 decennial censuses became a regular feature (2). Both statements are correct." },
    "325": { correct: "a", correctText: "Union of States", exp: "In the Draft Constitution presented by Dr. B.R. Ambedkar (4 November 1948), India was described as a “Union of States.” Not a “Federation/Autonomous/Subsidiary” of states." },
    "326": { correct: "a", correctText: "Cyril Radcliffe", exp: "Sir Cyril Radcliffe chaired the Boundary Commissions that demarcated the India-Pakistan borders in 1947. Mortimer Durand (Durand Line) and Henry McMahon (McMahon Line) drew other boundaries." },
    "327": { correct: "c", correctText: "Richard Wellesley", exp: "The College of Fort William (Calcutta) was established by Governor-General Lord (Richard) Wellesley in 1800. Not by Hastings, Cornwallis or Bentinck." },
    "328": { correct: "a", correctText: "Fort William College", exp: "Henry T. Colebrooke was a Professor of Sanskrit at Fort William College, Calcutta. He was a noted orientalist linked with the Asiatic Society, but his professorship was at Fort William College." },
    "329": { correct: "a", correctText: "H. St. Clair Wilkins", exp: "The Bombay Secretariat (1870s, Gothic Revival) was designed by the architect Colonel Henry St Clair Wilkins. The other names were patrons/industrialists, not the architect." },
    "330": { correct: "c", correctText: "Anglo-Gurkha War", exp: "Simla (Shimla) was founded as a hill station during/after the Anglo-Gurkha (Anglo-Nepalese) War of 1814–16, for billeting troops and guarding the frontier. Not the Maratha, Burmese or Afghan wars." },
    "331": { correct: "c", correctText: "Indians were never admitted to IMS", exp: "This is not correct — Indians were eventually admitted to the Indian Medical Service. The IMS began in the 18th century, recruited by competitive examination, and was initially meant to care for the troops — those statements are correct." },
    "332": { correct: "c", correctText: "1865", exp: "The first telegraphic connection between Europe and India was established in 1865 (the Indo-European Telegraph line). Not 1851, 1854 or 1871." },
    "333": { correct: "b", correctText: "2 (i.e., two statements are correct)", exp: "Two statements are correct: private investors got free land (1) and a guaranteed 5% return even on losses (2) — the “guarantee system.” Statement 3 (“jointly managed with the government”) is wrong; the companies managed the railways. So two are correct." },
    "334": { correct: "b", correctText: "2 (i.e., two statements are correct)", exp: "Statement 1 is wrong — flintlock muskets did not work reliably in wet weather. Statement 2 (bayonets made muskets effective in close combat) and statement 3 (mobile/manoeuvrable cannon barrels) are correct. So two statements are correct." },
    "335": { correct: "a", correctText: "John Lawrence", exp: "Viceroy John Lawrence was the first to officially shift his Council to Simla in the summer season (making it the summer capital). Not Dalhousie, Mayo or Bentinck." },
    "336": { correct: "c", correctText: "endorsed the Despatch of 1854 with greater emphasis on primary education", exp: "The Hunter Commission (1882) endorsed Wood’s Despatch of 1854 and laid greater stress on primary and secondary education. It neither deprecated university education nor overruled the 1854 Despatch." },
    "337": { correct: "a", correctText: "Lord Auckland", exp: "Governor-General Lord Auckland believed (1836) that Russian designs were an imminent peril to India’s security, a view that led to the First Anglo-Afghan War. Palmerston, Canning and Burnes are not the intended answer." },
    "338": { correct: "a", correctText: "Strengthening Afghanistan as a buffer against Russia", exp: "Early-19th-century British policy aimed at maintaining Afghanistan as a friendly buffer state against Russian expansion (the “Great Game”). It did not aim at annexation or promoting Russian influence." },
    "339": { correct: "b", correctText: "The ally was free to enter into agreements with other rulers or engage in warfare", exp: "This was NOT a term of Wellesley’s Subsidiary Alliance — in fact the ally lost the freedom to make agreements or wage war independently. The British protected the ally, stationed a contingent, and the ally paid for it — those were the actual terms." },
    "340": { correct: "b", correctText: "Awadh", exp: "Lord Dalhousie described Awadh (Oudh) as “a cherry that will drop into our mouth one day” before annexing it (1856) on grounds of misgovernment. Not Delhi, Jhansi or Gwalior." },
    "341": { correct: "c", correctText: "Statement I is true but Statement II is false", exp: "Statement I is true — the Poona Pact provided 151 reserved seats for the depressed classes through a joint electorate. Statement II is false — Ambedkar did not withdraw from politics for a decade; he remained very active. Hence I true, II false." },
    "342": { correct: "d", correctText: "The All India Depressed Classes Association favoured Ambedkar’s demand for separate electorate for the depressed classes.", exp: "This is not correct — the M.C. Rajah-led Depressed Classes Association actually opposed separate electorates (Rajah favoured joint electorates, leading to the Rajah-Moonje Pact). The other statements about the Association are correct." },
    "343": { correct: "b", correctText: "Separate electorates for untouchables", exp: "The All India Depressed Classes Leaders’ Conference at Bombay (1931) demanded separate electorates for the untouchables (Ambedkar’s position). Not universal suffrage, minority reservation or a unitary state as the core demand." },
    "344": { correct: "d", correctText: "Ahirs and Kurmis", exp: "The Triveni Sangh (formed after WWI in Bihar) was an organisation of backward castes — the Ahirs (Yadavs), Kurmis and Koeris. Hence Ahirs and Kurmis (among the options)." },
    "345": { correct: "c", correctText: "E.V. Ramaswamy Naicker", exp: "The Self-Respect Movement was initiated by E.V. Ramaswamy Naicker (“Periyar”) in Tamil Nadu. Not by Ambedkar, Phule or Nehru." },
    "346": { correct: "d", correctText: "Amritlal Vithaldas Thakkar", exp: "Amritlal Vithaldas Thakkar (“Thakkar Bapa”) founded the Bhil Seva Mandal in 1922. Not Gidumal, Gurusaday Dutt or D.K. Karve." },
    "347": { correct: "a", correctText: "Maharashtra", exp: "The Kalaram temple (site of Ambedkar’s 1930 temple-entry satyagraha) is at Nashik, Maharashtra. Not in Kerala, Tamil Nadu or Gujarat." },
    "348": { correct: "d", correctText: "It supported the call given by the Congress to boycott elections in 1920.", exp: "This is not correct — the Justice Party did NOT support the Congress’s 1920 election boycott; it contested and took office. Its demands for communal representation, its landowning/middle-class base, and the 28 reserved seats under Montagu-Chelmsford are correct." },
    "349": { correct: "b", correctText: "Alexander Reed", exp: "The Ryotwari experiment was started by Captain Alexander Reed (and developed by Thomas Munro) in the Madras/Baramahal region. Not by Henry Dundas, David Ricardo or Elphinstone." },
